2022-05-17","#martaf",{"surface":483},[484,500],{"type":485,"graphic":486},"front",[487,491,494,498],{"n":488,"url":126,"height":489,"width":490,"desc":127},"screen","3744px","5616px",{"n":492,"url":493,"height":489,"width":490,"desc":127},"print","ISic001302.jpg",{"n":488,"url":495,"height":496,"width":497,"desc":127},"ISic001302_leftthreequarter_tiled.tif","3168px","4752px",{"n":492,"url":499,"height":496,"width":497,"desc":127},"ISic001302_leftthreequarter.jpg",{"type":501,"graphic":502},"rear",[503,505],{"n":488,"url":504,"height":489,"width":490,"desc":127},"ISic001302_rear_tiled.tif",{"n":492,"url":506,"height":489,"width":490,"desc":127},"ISic001302_rear.jpg",{"body":508},{"div":509},[510,555,564,567,569,592],{"type":142,"xml:space":511,"xml:lang":139,"resp":512,"ab":513},"preserve","#martaf #AA",{"lb":514,"w":524,"g":537,"persName":544,"hi":550},[515,517,519,521,523],{"n":516},"1",{"n":518},"2",{"n":520},"4",{"n":522},"5",{"n":86},[525,529,533,534,535,536],{"expan":526},{"abbr":527,"ex":528},"Θ","εοῖς",{"expan":530},{"abbr":531,"ex":532},"Κ","ατακθονίοις","ἡ","φιλόστολος","ἔζησε","ἔτη",[538,541],{"_":539,"ref":540},"❦","#ivy-leaf",{"_":542,"ref":543},"·","#interpunct",{"type":545,"name":546,"lb":549},"attested",[547,548],"Ἰουλία","Γαλήνη",{"n":98},{"rend":551,"num":552},"supraline",{"_":553,"value":554},"λγ","33",{"type":556,"resp":481,"listApp":557},"apparatus",{"app":558},[559,561],{"note":560},"Text based on photographs",{"loc":562,"note":563},"line 4","In the comment Kaibel cautiously suggests to correct φιλόστολος in φιλόστοργος",{"type":565,"xml:lang":224,"resp":455,"p":566},"translation","To the subterranean deities. Ioulia Galene, 'philostolos', lived for 33 years.",{"type":565,"xml:lang":415,"source":170,"p":568},"Agli dèi inferi. Giulia Galene, la φιλόστολος, visse trentatré anni.",{"type":570,"p":571},"commentary",{"_":572,"foreign":573,"ref":589},"The epitaph presents the name of the deceased, an epithet and the indication of her age. The reading of the epithet is certain: for this reason, as Kaibel already noticed, there is no need to amend the text. The epithet  does not seem to be attested elsewhere in Greek texts; it could indicate “the lover of the army or of the fleet ()” or “the lover of the stola ()”. Rizzone (2009: 202) translates the epithet as “mistress of the fleet”, but already Bertucci (1846: 32) and more recently Korhonen (2004: 213) and Cassia (2020) believe that the epithet refers to  and expresses the status of Ioulia Galene as a freeborn Roman matron. As a matter of fact, the deceased was a Roman citizen, as attested by the nomen . Even though the name Γαλήνη may seem to be a speaking name (“stillness of the sea”) related to the fleet, it seems to have been a female name quite common in the imperial age. Ioulia could have used the epithet as a synonym of the expressions  or  recurring in several inscriptions and papyri, especially from the 2nd-3rd century CE (Cassia 2020: 66-68). The compound would thus be in line with other epithets found in funerary inscriptions and inspired by the family and social virtues of the deceased, such as  or . See also .",[574,575,577,579,580,581,583,585,587],{"_":534,"xml:lang":139},{"_":576,"xml:lang":139},"στόλος",{"_":578,"xml:lang":139},"στολή",{"_":578,"xml:lang":139},{"_":547,"xml:lang":139},{"_":582,"xml:lang":419},"stolata femina",{"_":584,"xml:lang":139},"ματρῶνα στολάτα",{"_":586,"xml:lang":139},"φιλότεκνος",{"_":588,"xml:lang":139},"φίλανδρος",{"_":590,"target":591},"EpiCum476","http://epicum.istc.cnr.it/EPICUM/EpiCUM476",{"type":593,"listBibl":594},"bibliography",[595,608],{"type":142,"bibl":596},[597,602,605],{"type":145,"n":146,"citedRange":598,"ptr":600,"ref":601},{"ref":599},{"_":149,"target":150},{"target":152},{"_":154,"target":154},{"type":145,"n":158,"citedRange":159,"ptr":603,"ref":604},{"target":161},{"_":163,"target":163},{"author":167,"date":168,"ptr":606,"ref":607},{"target":170},{"_":172,"target":172},{"type":176,"bibl":609},[610,61